1. Introduction

1a. Welcome

Thank you for visiting my portfolio! I’m Kevin Chen, a Data Analyst in the healthcare insurance sector, specializing in transforming complex data into actionable insights. This portfolio highlights my work on a critical emergency response initiative, showcasing how advanced analytics—using SQL and Tableau—can enhance insurance member support during crises, with a focus on analyzing the impacts of the Los Angeles wildfires on insurance members.

1b. Scenario Background

This portfolio demonstrates advanced analytics capabilities in disaster recovery through a comprehensive analysis of healthcare member support following the wildfire in Los Angeles. Our healthcare insurance company launched a data-driven recovery program that integrates detailed damage assessment data (DINS - Damage Information Network System) with member information to provide targeted assistance to those most affected.
Through the integration of damage assessment data with member demographics and insurance information, we created a comprehensive support strategy that enables precise, needs-based assistance for our affected members during their recovery process. This approach showcases how combining governmental damage assessment data with internal member information can transform post-disaster recovery efforts in healthcare management.

1c. Technical Skills Showcase

This portfolio demonstrates my expertise in transforming complex disaster recovery data into actionable insights through three key technical areas:

Advanced SQL Analysis

I leverage sophisticated SQL querying techniques to analyze member impacts and optimize support strategies:
  • Complex data integration using CTEs and window functions to merge DINS damage assessments with member data
  • Geographic analysis through joins of structural damage data with member locations
  • Member risk assessment using multi-dimensional analysis combining damage severity, coverage types, and member status
  • Temporal pattern analysis tracking member status changes and premium distributions over time
  • Status transition analysis using state matrices and flow tracking

Interactive Tableau Dashboards

My Tableau visualizations transform complex disaster recovery data into intuitive, actionable insights:
  • Interactive damage severity maps showing member impact distribution
  • Multi-layer visualizations combining property damage with insurance coverage analysis
  • Dynamic member status tracking dashboards with drill-down capabilities
  • Recovery timeline forecasting with milestone tracking
  • Customizable filters for plan tiers and coverage types to support targeted assistance programs

R Markdown Documentation

The document you are currently reading demonstrates my R Markdown documentation capabilities:
  • Professional structuring of analysis workflows and findings
  • Clear organization with detailed table of contents
  • Integration of technical content with business context
  • Embedding of SQL queries and visualization examples
  • Creation of stakeholder-friendly technical documentation
  • Implementation of cross-referencing and clickable section shortcuts

Throughout this portfolio, you’ll see how these technical skills come together to support critical decision-making in post-disaster member support, demonstrating both analytical rigor and practical application in a real-world scenario. Each visualization, analysis, and section of this document is crafted to deliver clear, actionable insights for stakeholders managing disaster recovery efforts.


2. Exploring Data Sources


2a. Official Government Data

The following government datasets provides the foundation upon which the analysis can be built.


CAL FIRE Data

Dataset: DINS_2025_Palisades_Public_View.csv, DINS_2025_Eaton_Public_View.csv
Source: California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection
URL: https://data.ca.gov/dataset/cal-fire
Content:

  • Wildfire risk zones
  • Geographic information
  • Risk levels by area
  • Property damage assessments
  • Structural impact classifications
LA County Evacuation Zones

Dataset: Maximum_Extent_Evacuation_Zones.csv
Source: Los Angeles County Open Data
URL: https://data.lacounty.gov/
Content:

  • Emergency evacuation boundaries
  • Zone classifications
  • Geographic coordinates
  • Population impact estimates
  • Evacuation timeline data

2b. Randomly Generated Data

As a supplement to the government data, the insurance member dataset was randomly generated using a combination of AI (ChatGPT) and Python.

The following Python code was used to generate member Dataset:

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import random
import string
from datetime import datetime, timedelta
from typing import List, Dict, Tuple

class InsuranceMemberGenerator:
    def __init__(self, seed: int = 42):
        try:
            self.seed = seed
            np.random.seed(seed)
            random.seed(seed)

            # Names Constants
            self.male_names = ['James', 'John', 'Robert', 'Michael', 'William', 'David', 'Richard', 'Joseph', 'Thomas', 'Charles', 'Christopher', 'Daniel', 'Matthew', 'Anthony', 'Donald', 'Mark', 'Paul', 'Steven', 'Andrew', 'Kenneth']
            self.female_names = ['Mary', 'Patricia', 'Jennifer', 'Linda', 'Elizabeth', 'Barbara', 'Susan', 'Jessica', 'Sarah', 'Karen', 'Lisa', 'Nancy', 'Betty', 'Margaret', 'Sandra', 'Ashley', 'Dorothy', 'Emma', 'Emily', 'Laura']
            self.last_names = self._generate_unique_last_names(4000)
            self.street_names = ['Main', 'Oak', 'Maple', 'Cedar', 'Pine', 'Elm', 'Washington', 'Lake', 'Hill', 'Park',
                                'River', 'Valley', 'Mountain', 'Spring', 'Sunset', 'Forest', 'Meadow', 'Ocean', 'Beach', 'Highland']

            # City and ZIP code distributions
            self.city_distribution = {'Los Angeles': 0.90, 'Malibu': 0.05, 'Santa Monica': 0.05}
            self.zip_codes = {
                'Los Angeles': {'90272': 0.60, '90290': 0.10, '90049': 0.10, '91356': 0.05, '91357': 0.05, '91316': 0.05, '91436': 0.05},
                'Malibu': {'90263': 0.40, '90264': 0.30, '90265': 0.30},
                'Santa Monica': {'90401': 0.20, '90402': 0.20, '90403': 0.20, '90404': 0.20, '90405': 0.20}
            }

            # Premium rates
            self.premium_rates = {
                ('Bronze', 'Individual'): 300,
                ('Bronze', 'Family'): 500,
                ('Silver', 'Individual'): 500,
                ('Silver', 'Family'): 700,
                ('Gold', 'Individual'): 700,
                ('Gold', 'Family'): 900,
                ('Platinum', 'Individual'): 900,
                ('Platinum', 'Family'): 1200
            }

        except Exception as e:
            raise RuntimeError(f"Failed to initialize generator: {str(e)}")

    def _generate_unique_last_names(self, count: int) -> List[str]:
        base_names = ['Smith', 'Johnson', 'Williams', 'Brown', 'Jones', 'Garcia', 'Miller', 'Davis', 'Rodriguez', 'Martinez']
        suffixes = ['', ' Jr', ' Sr', '-Smith', '-Jones', '-Williams', '-Davis', '-Miller', '-Brown', '-Garcia']

        names = []
        for name in base_names:
            for suffix in suffixes:
                names.append(f"{name}{suffix}")

        # Add more variations if needed
        while len(names) < count:
            name = random.choice(base_names)
            suffix = ''.join(random.choices(string.ascii_uppercase, k=2))
            names.append(f"{name}-{suffix}")

        return names[:count]

    def _generate_age_based_dob(self) -> datetime:
        age_ranges = {
            (12, 17): 0.05,
            (18, 24): 0.18,
            (25, 44): 0.35,
            (45, 64): 0.25,
            (65, 90): 0.17
        }

        # Select age range
        age_range = random.choices(list(age_ranges.keys()), weights=list(age_ranges.values()))[0]

        # Generate random age within range
        age = random.randint(age_range[0], age_range[1])

        # Calculate DOB
        today = datetime(2024, 1, 1)  # Fixed reference date
        dob = today - timedelta(days=age*365 + random.randint(0, 365))
        return dob

    def _generate_address(self) -> tuple:
        # Generate street address, city, and ZIP code
        street_num = random.randint(100, 9999)
        street_name = random.choice(self.street_names)

        # Select city based on distribution
        city = random.choices(list(self.city_distribution.keys()),
                            weights=list(self.city_distribution.values()))[0]

        # Select ZIP code based on city
        zip_code = random.choices(list(self.zip_codes[city].keys()),
                                weights=list(self.zip_codes[city].values()))[0]

        return (f"{street_num} {street_name} Street", city, zip_code)

    def generate_dataset(self, total_rows: int = 12041, member_rows: int = 3500) -> pd.DataFrame:
        
        # Generate the complete insurance member dataset
        if member_rows > total_rows - 1:
            raise ValueError("member_rows cannot exceed total_rows - 1")

        if total_rows < 2 or member_rows < 1:
            raise ValueError("total_rows must be at least 2 and member_rows must be positive")

        # Initialize DataFrame with row numbers
        df = pd.DataFrame({'RowNumber': range(1, total_rows + 1)})

        # Randomly select member rows (excluding row 1)
        member_indices = np.random.choice(range(2, total_rows + 1), size=member_rows, replace=False)

        # Generate member data
        member_data = []
        used_member_ids = set()
        used_addresses = set()

        for idx in member_indices:
            # Generate unique MemberID
            while True:
                member_id = f"LA1{str(random.randint(0, 999999)).zfill(6)}"
                if member_id not in used_member_ids:
                    used_member_ids.add(member_id)
                    break

            # Generate gender and name
            gender = random.choices(['M', 'F'], weights=[0.49, 0.51])[0]
            first_name = random.choice(self.male_names if gender == 'M' else self.female_names)
            last_name = random.choice(self.last_names)

            # Generate dates
            dob = self._generate_age_based_dob()

            # Calculate enrollment date range
            min_enrollment_date = max(
                datetime(2000, 1, 1),  # Not earlier than 2000
                dob + timedelta(days=18*365)  # Must be at least 18 years after DOB
            )
            max_enrollment_date = datetime(2024, 12, 31)

            # Ensure valid enrollment date range
            if min_enrollment_date >= max_enrollment_date:
                min_enrollment_date = max_enrollment_date - timedelta(days=365)

            # Generate enrollment date
            days_range = (max_enrollment_date - min_enrollment_date).days
            enrollment_date = min_enrollment_date + timedelta(days=random.randint(0, max(0, days_range)))

            # Generate status change date
            max_status_date = datetime(2024, 12, 31)
            days_until_max = (max_status_date - enrollment_date).days

            if days_until_max <= 0:
                # If enrollment is on or after max date, use enrollment date
                status_change_date = enrollment_date
            elif days_until_max == 1:
                # If only one day left, use either enrollment date or next day
                status_change_date = enrollment_date + timedelta(days=random.choice([0, 1]))
            else:
                # Normal case: random date between enrollment and max date
                status_change_date = enrollment_date + timedelta(
                    days=random.randint(0, days_until_max)
                )

            # Generate address
            while True:
                address = self._generate_address()
                if address[0] not in used_addresses:
                    used_addresses.add(address[0])
                    break

            # Generate plan details
            plan_tier = random.choices(['Bronze', 'Silver', 'Gold', 'Platinum'],
                                    weights=[0.40, 0.30, 0.20, 0.10])[0]
            coverage_type = random.choices(['Individual', 'Family'],
                                        weights=[0.65, 0.35])[0]
            monthly_premium = self.premium_rates[(plan_tier, coverage_type)]

            # Generate status
            member_status = random.choices(['Active', 'Terminated', 'Suspended', 'Pending'],
                                        weights=[0.65, 0.20, 0.10, 0.05])[0]

            member_data.append({
                'RowNumber': idx,
                'MemberID': member_id,
                'FirstName': first_name,
                'LastName': last_name,
                'DOB': dob,
                'Gender': gender,
                'Street': address[0],
                'City': address[1],
                'State': 'CA',
                'ZipCode': address[2],
                'EnrollmentDate': enrollment_date,
                'PlanTier': plan_tier,
                'CoverageType': coverage_type,
                'MonthlyPremium': monthly_premium,
                'MemberStatus': member_status,
                'LastStatusChangeDate': status_change_date
            })

        # Create member DataFrame
        member_df = pd.DataFrame(member_data)

        # Merge with main DataFrame
        df = df.merge(member_df, how='left', on='RowNumber')

        return df

    def save_dataset(self, df: pd.DataFrame, filename: str):
        df.to_csv(filename, index=False)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    generator = InsuranceMemberGenerator(seed=42)
    df = generator.generate_dataset()
    generator.save_dataset(df, "insurance_members.csv")

Scenario I: Critical Member Identification

A. Setting the Stage

When wildfires swept through Los Angeles County, our Emergency Response Team faced an urgent challenge: How do we quickly identify and reach our most vulnerable members? With thousands potentially affected, we needed to rapidly assess who was in immediate danger and required priority assistance.

B. Ad Hoc Request

Which active members are currently located in the Palisades fire zone and need immediate contact?
SELECT 
    MemberID,
    CAST(FirstName AS VARCHAR) || ' ' || CAST(LastName AS VARCHAR) as FullName,
    City,
    ZipCode,
    IncidentName,
    MemberStatus
FROM Tableau_Dataset
WHERE IncidentName = 'PALISADES'
    AND MemberStatus = 'Active'
ORDER BY ZipCode
LIMIT 5;

C. In-Depth Analysis

How are our members distributed across evacuation zones, and where should we focus our immediate emergency response efforts?
WITH MemberLocation AS (
    SELECT 
        City,
        ZipCode,
        IncidentName,
        COUNT(*) as TotalMembers,
        COUNT(CASE WHEN MemberStatus = 'Active' THEN 1 END) as ActiveMembers,
        COUNT(CASE WHEN CoverageType = 'Family' THEN 1 END) as FamilyPlans
    FROM Tableau_Dataset
    WHERE ZipCode IS NOT NULL
        AND IncidentName IN ('PALISADES', 'EATON')
    GROUP BY City, ZipCode, IncidentName
)
SELECT 
    IncidentName,
    City,
    ZipCode,
    TotalMembers,
    ActiveMembers,
    FamilyPlans,
    ROUND(CAST(ActiveMembers AS FLOAT) / NULLIF(TotalMembers, 0), 4) * 100 AS ActiveMemberPercentage 
FROM MemberLocation
ORDER BY TotalMembers DESC
LIMIT 5;

Scenario II: Structure Impact Analysis

A. Setting the Stage

The initial damage reports came in fragmented and unclear. We needed to understand not just where the fires were, but how different types of structures were affected. Our Emergency Response Team required a clear picture: which areas had the most severe structural damage, and where were our members most at risk?

B. Ad Hoc Request

What is the current distribution of structural damage across different building types in the Palisades Fire area, and how many members are affected in each category?
SELECT 
    StructureType,
    Damage,
    COUNT(*) as structure_count,
    COUNT(DISTINCT MemberID) as affected_members
FROM Tableau_Dataset
WHERE IncidentName = 'PALISADES'
    AND StructureType IS NOT NULL 
GROUP BY StructureType, Damage
ORDER BY structure_count DESC
LIMIT 5;

C. In-Depth Analysis

How do structure types correlate with damage severity, member impact, and financial exposure across both fire incidents, and which areas represent the highest risk for our insured members?
WITH damage_metrics AS (
    SELECT 
        IncidentName,
        StructureType,
        Damage,
        -- Count structures
        COUNT(*) as structure_count,
        -- Count affected members
        COUNT(DISTINCT MemberID) as member_count,
        -- Calculate damage severity weight
        SUM(CASE 
            WHEN Damage = 'Destroyed' THEN 5
            WHEN Damage = 'Major' THEN 4
            WHEN Damage = 'Minor' THEN 3
            WHEN Damage = 'Affected' THEN 2
            WHEN Damage = 'Inaccessible' THEN 1
            ELSE 0 
        END) as damage_severity_score
    FROM Tableau_Dataset
    WHERE IncidentName IN ('PALISADES', 'EATON')
        AND StructureType IS NOT NULL
    GROUP BY IncidentName, StructureType, Damage
),
incident_summary AS (
    SELECT 
        IncidentName,
        StructureType,
        SUM(structure_count) as total_structures,
        SUM(member_count) as total_affected_members,
        SUM(damage_severity_score) as total_damage_score
    FROM damage_metrics
    GROUP BY IncidentName, StructureType
)
SELECT 
    i.*,
    -- Calculate risk priority
    DENSE_RANK() OVER (
        PARTITION BY IncidentName 
        ORDER BY total_damage_score DESC
    ) as risk_priority,
    -- Calculate impact priority
    DENSE_RANK() OVER (
        PARTITION BY IncidentName 
        ORDER BY total_affected_members DESC
    ) as impact_priority
FROM incident_summary i
ORDER BY 
    total_damage_score DESC,
    impact_priority
LIMIT 5;
5 records
IncidentName StructureType total_structures total_affected_members total_damage_score risk_priority impact_priority
EATON Single Family Residence Single Story 9410 2574 21 1 1
EATON Single Family Residence Multi Story 2457 672 10 2 3
EATON Utility Misc Structure 5685 1520 9 3 2
PALISADES Single Family Residence Multi Story 5350 1575 0 1 1
PALISADES Single Family Residence Single Story 3682 1087 0 1 2

E. Key Findings

1. Critical Impact Assessmen
  • EATON fire zone shows the highest concentration of affected members (56.6% of members affected) despite having a lower percentage of damaged structures (27.3%), indicating a critical mismatch between structural damage and member impact.
  • Single Family Residences in EATON area represent the highest risk priority, with 9,410 affected structures impacting 2,574 members.
2. Damage Distribution Pattern
  • Residential structures show a binary damage pattern: either severe damage (destroyed/major) or minimal impact, with few intermediate cases.
  • This pattern suggests clear impact zone boundaries, enabling more targeted response strategies.
3. Member Risk Concentration
  • Multi-story residential buildings show disproportionate member impact relative to structure count.
  • In the PALISADES area, 5,350 multi-story residences affected 1,575 members, indicating higher population density in these structures.
4. Geographic Risk Stratification
  • Clear correlation between evacuation zones and structure damage levels.
  • Evacuation warnings form distinct buffer zones around areas with the highest structural damage, providing a predictive indicator for potential damage spread.


Scenario III: Regional Coverage Analysis

A. Setting the Stage

As response teams mobilized, a critical question emerged: were we seeing patterns in how the fires affected different communities? Understanding the demographic and geographic distribution of our affected members became crucial for tailoring our support services and allocating resources effectively.

B. Ad Hoc Request

What is the distribution of members and their insurance tiers across different cities, and which areas show the highest concentration of premium plans (Gold/Platinum)?
SELECT 
    City,
    COUNT(DISTINCT MemberID) as total_members,
    SUM(CASE WHEN PlanTier IN ('Gold', 'Platinum') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as premium_plan_count,
    ROUND(CAST(AVG(CAST(MonthlyPremium AS FLOAT)) AS NUMERIC), 2) as avg_monthly_premium,
    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN CoverageType = 'Family' THEN MemberID END) as family_coverage_count
FROM Tableau_Dataset
WHERE MemberID IS NOT NULL
    AND City IS NOT NULL
GROUP BY City
ORDER BY total_members DESC
LIMIT 5;

C. In-Depth Analysis

How does the impact of the wildfires on insurance members vary across different cities in terms of member demographics, plan types, premium rates, and property damage?
WITH age_categorized AS (
    SELECT 
        City,
        CASE 
            WHEN strftime('%Y', 'now') - strftime('%Y', DOB) < 18 THEN '1-17'
            WHEN strftime('%Y', 'now') - strftime('%Y', DOB) < 25 THEN '18-24'
            WHEN strftime('%Y', 'now') - strftime('%Y', DOB) < 45 THEN '25-44'
            WHEN strftime('%Y', 'now') - strftime('%Y', DOB) < 65 THEN '45-64'
            ELSE '65+'
        END as age_group,
        PlanTier,
        CoverageType,
        CAST(MonthlyPremium AS INTEGER) as monthly_premium,
        Damage,
        MemberStatus
    FROM Tableau_Dataset
    WHERE City IS NOT NULL
)
SELECT 
    City,
    COUNT(*) as total_members,
    SUM(CASE WHEN age_group = '65+' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as elderly_count,
    SUM(CASE WHEN age_group = '1-17' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as minor_count,
    SUM(CASE WHEN PlanTier IN ('Gold', 'Platinum') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as premium_plan_count,
    SUM(CASE WHEN CoverageType = 'Family' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as family_coverage_count,
    SUM(CASE WHEN Damage LIKE 'Destroyed%' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as severe_damage_count,
    ROUND(AVG(monthly_premium), 2) as avg_premium,
    SUM(CASE WHEN MemberStatus = 'Active' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as active_members,
    ROUND(CAST(SUM(CASE WHEN age_group IN ('1-17', '65+') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) * 100.0 / COUNT(*) AS FLOAT), 2) as vulnerable_population_pct
FROM age_categorized
GROUP BY City
HAVING SUM(CASE WHEN MemberStatus = 'Active' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) > 0
ORDER BY total_members DESC
LIMIT 5;

Scenario IV: Priority Impact & Team Distribution

A. Setting the Stage

Our response teams were stretched thin across multiple affected areas. We needed a systematic way to assign cases and measure intervention effectiveness. How could we ensure our most vulnerable members received appropriate support while maintaining sustainable workloads for our teams?

B. Ad Hoc Request

What is the initial distribution of priority scores across different age groups and coverage types, and how does this affect our team workload allocation?
WITH priority_scoring AS (
    SELECT 
        MemberID,
        CASE 
            WHEN CAST(strftime('%Y', '2025') - strftime('%Y', DOB) AS INTEGER) < 18 THEN 1
            WHEN CAST(strftime('%Y', '2025') - strftime('%Y', DOB) AS INTEGER) >= 65 THEN 2
            ELSE 0
        END AS age_points,
        CASE WHEN CoverageType = 'Family' THEN 2 ELSE 0 END AS coverage_points,
        CASE WHEN PlanTier IN ('Platinum', 'Gold') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS tier_points
    FROM Tableau_Dataset
    WHERE MemberID IS NOT NULL
)
SELECT 
    (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) AS priority_score,
    COUNT(*) as member_count,
    ROUND(COUNT(*) * 100.0 / SUM(COUNT(*)) OVER (), 2) as percentage,
    CASE 
        WHEN (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) >= 5 THEN 'Team Alpha'
        WHEN (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) = 4 THEN 'Team Beta'
        WHEN (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) = 3 THEN 'Team Gamma'
        ELSE 'Team Delta'
    END as assigned_team
FROM priority_scoring
GROUP BY priority_score
ORDER BY priority_score DESC;
5 records
priority_score member_count percentage assigned_team

C. In-Depth Analysis

How effectively are our response teams handling their assigned workloads based on member priority scores, and are there any significant imbalances in case complexity or resource distribution that need to be addressed?
WITH member_scoring AS (
    SELECT DISTINCT  -- Add DISTINCT to ensure unique member records
        MemberID,
        CoverageType,
        PlanTier,
        MemberStatus,
        Damage,
        MonthlyPremium,
        CASE 
            WHEN CAST(strftime('%Y', '2025') - strftime('%Y', DOB) AS INTEGER) < 18 THEN 1
            WHEN CAST(strftime('%Y', '2025') - strftime('%Y', DOB) AS INTEGER) >= 65 THEN 2
            ELSE 0
        END AS age_points,
        CASE WHEN CoverageType = 'Family' THEN 2 ELSE 0 END AS coverage_points,
        CASE WHEN PlanTier IN ('Platinum', 'Gold') THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS tier_points
    FROM Tableau_Dataset
    WHERE MemberID IS NOT NULL
),
priority_assignment AS (
    SELECT 
        *,
        (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) AS priority_score,
        CASE 
            WHEN (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) >= 5 THEN 'Team Alpha'
            WHEN (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) = 4 THEN 'Team Beta'
            WHEN (age_points + coverage_points + tier_points + 1) = 3 THEN 'Team Gamma'
            ELSE 'Team Delta'
        END AS assigned_team
    FROM member_scoring
)
SELECT 
    assigned_team,
    COUNT(DISTINCT MemberID) as total_cases,  -- Count distinct members
    ROUND(AVG(priority_score), 2) as avg_priority_score,
    SUM(CASE WHEN Damage IN ('Destroyed', 'Major', 'Destroyed ', 'Major ') 
             OR Damage LIKE '%Destroyed%' 
             OR Damage LIKE '%Major%' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as high_damage_cases,
    SUM(CASE WHEN CoverageType = 'Family' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as family_cases,
    SUM(CASE WHEN priority_score >= 4 THEN 1 END) as high_priority_cases,
    ROUND(COUNT(DISTINCT MemberID) * 100.0 / SUM(COUNT(DISTINCT MemberID)) OVER (), 2) as workload_percentage,
    ROUND(SUM(MonthlyPremium), 2) as total_monthly_premium
FROM priority_assignment
GROUP BY assigned_team
ORDER BY avg_priority_score DESC;

E. Key Findings

1. Team Distribution Achievement
  • The actual workload distribution (10.74/24.55/19.80/44.91) closely aligns with the target allocation (10/20/30/40)
  • This indicates successful implementation of the priority scoring system
2. Family Coverage Concentration
  • All family coverage cases are handled by the more experienced teams (Alpha and Beta)
  • This aligns with the higher priority scores given to family coverage (+2 points)
3. High-Priority Case Management
  • Teams Alpha and Beta handle all cases with priority scores 4 and above
  • This ensures the most complex cases are managed by the most experienced teams
4. Resource Allocation Efficiency
  • Despite handling fewer cases, Teams Alpha and Beta manage higher-complexity situations
  • Team Delta handles the highest volume but less complex cases, matching their resource capacity
